==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Crypt
<hw>Crypt</hw> <pr>(kr⟦icr⟧pt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>crypta</ets> vault, crypt, Gr. <grk>kry`pth</grk>, fr.
<grk>kry`ptein</grk> to hide. See <er>Grot</er>, <er>Grotto</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A vault wholly or partly under ground; especially, a
vault under a church, whether used for burial purposes or for a
subterranean chapel or oratory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Priesthood works out its task age after age, . . . treasuring in
convents and <qex>crypts</qex> the few fossils of antique learning.</q>
<rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My knees are bowed in <qex>crypt</qex> and shrine.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A simple gland, glandular cavity,
or tube; a follicle; <as>as, the <ex>crypts</ex> of Lieberk⟦uum⟧hn, the
simple tubular glands of the small intestines</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cryptal</ent>⟦br⟧
